Title: Bodywork - every day!
WorkoutDescription: Body work: 10 min foam rolling followed by 10 min of stretching Foam Roll 10 min - Light foam rolling, spending approximately 1-2 minutes on each of the following: -Calves -Soleus -IT bands -Hamstrings -Gluteals -Adductors -Lower back -Scapular muscles. Spend extra time on any particularly tight/painful areas. Be very careful not to roll on joints, or other areas with thin soft tissue cover. Stretching: Focus on targeting the flexibility of the glutes, hamstrings, quads, calves, and hipflexors. Ease into all stretching activities with muscles that are already warmed up. Hold all stretches for at least 30s.

Title: TRX (custom routine)
WorkoutDescription: All exercises for 2 sets of 10 reps. Take 30 seconds between exercises. - Single Leg Squat - Sprinters Start - TRX Suspended Lunge - Hamstring Curl - Atomic Push-up - Side Plank (work up to 30 seconds each side) - Plank (work up to 30 seconds) - TRX Back Extentions - Single Arm Rotating Row - Swimmers Pull - Standing Y 2 sets of 12 reps of: -Monster Walk -Eccentric Calf Raises

Title: Master's Swim
WorkoutDescription: Swim with your master's group and summarize what you did in the notes

Title: Aerobic Z1 Ride #3 (2 X 10 min low cadence)
WorkoutDescription: **Make sure you descend the pace by getting faster throughout the workout. Start at the lower end of zone 1 and work your way toward the top by the end of the workout. Keep cadence at 90-95+ throughout during base phase and 85-90 rpm during build phase unless using QT2 bike stimulation cadence chart (as given by coach). **Insert 2 X 10 minutes at Z1 and a cadence of 20-30rpm less than prior cadance. Do this during 2nd half of workout, with 5 min at ZR and normal cadance between each**

Title: Aerobic Run (Z1)
WorkoutDescription: Zone 1 Run. Make sure you descend the pace by getting faster throughout the workout. Start at the lower end of zone 1 and work your way toward the top by the end of the workout.
AthleteComments: *01/04/2018 Tara Strassburg: Solid run, especially after the jet lag earlier in the week!* *01/04/2018 Raul J Luzardo: Question, in the TP HR zones, what is the grey zone, I missed that on the seminar?* *01/04/2018 Tara Strassburg: It’s just the gap between ZR and Z1, they had to call it something in TP and “Grey zone” is what they came up with. It’s typically a 4-6 best window. The reason for it is because athletes tend to work the upper end of zones, so if we give them a ZR workout and the push the upper limit, they’re venturing into Z1. With the window, it gives a little more wiggle room to ensure that ZR truly is ZR!* *01/04/2018 Raul J Luzardo: Cool, thanks*

Title: Eccentric Calf Raises
WorkoutDescription: Do 3 sets of 12 reps on each leg. Each rep is carried out by standing on the ball of your foot (on a step), lowering slowly with one leg over a 2-3 second period (full range of motion), and then lifting back to the top with both feet quickly. These will help strengthen and stretch your calves.

WorkoutDescription: Do 3 sets of 12 reps on each leg. Title: Z2/Z3 Tempo Strength Power/Spinups
WorkoutDescription: Warmup 15 minutes easy spinning. Inclue today: POWERUPS: Bike 5 X 2 minute intervals starting in a gear that puts you at about 90rpm and high zone 2 (by HR). Every 30 seconds, add some resistance, but don't let your cadence slow. HR will rise into Z3. Ride 2 minute ZR recoveries between climbing intervals. SPINUPS: 5 x 2 minute intervals. Slowly spin-up to max rpm over the first 30 seconds until you can't pedal any faster (but no bouncing in the saddle!) Add a couple of gears but try to maintain the same cadence for 2 minutes. Ride 2 minutes ZR in-between. Ride any remaining time in zone 1. Cool down 10 minutes easy spinning.

AthleteComments: *04/02/2018 Raul Luzardo -  Coach: 3x 20 Miles laps, This was absolutely brutal, one of the hardest days in a bike I've had. A lot to learn and fix on this, if you have experience or know someone that do, I think we might need to ask some questions, I don't think regular riding is going to be enough to have a good Leadville* *04/03/2018 Tara Strassburg: I totally agree! Title: Texas 70.3 Swim
CoachComments: the key to a solid swim is going to be finding a fast set of toes and really working the draft - be smart out there and get after it!

Title: Texas 70.3 Bike
CoachComments: target HR on the bike is 150. keep cadence around 86-88rpm during the tailwind, and 90-92 during the headwind - don't let yourself get caught up in cadence any lower than that during the race! stay on top of nutrition. the body will likely be feeling the fatigue from the MTB race, so let's make sure you are dialing into how you are feeling on race day, and adjusting accordingly.
AthleteComments: *04/09/2018 Tara Strassburg: Can you go into Garmin Connect and save the .tcx file from this ride and send it to me? I will put together a post race analysis for you.*

Title: Texas 70.3 Run
CoachComments: let's go out at a 8:20 pace, and see where this puts your HR at mile 2-3 (once you settle in). if HR is above 160, ease up a bit and target 160. if HR is below 160, slowly dial up the pace until you hit it. hold steady until mile 10, and then let 'er rip!
AthleteComments: *04/09/2018 Tara Strassburg: Can you send me the .csv file from this run? Thanks!* *04/09/2018 Raul Luzardo -  Coach: CSV?* *04/09/2018 Tara Strassburg: When you are in Garmin Connect, you can save the .csv file (it’s usually in the top right hand corner in the settings). I can use it to put together a run analysis.*

Title: Aerobic Z1 Ride #3 (2 X 30 min low cadence)
WorkoutDescription: **Make sure you descend the pace by getting faster throughout the workout. Start at the lower end of zone 1 and work your way toward the top by the end of the workout. Keep cadence at 90-95+ throughout during base phase and 85-90 rpm during build phase unless using QT2 bike stimulation cadence chart (as given by coach). **Insert 2 X 30 minutes at Z1 and a cadence of 15-20rpm less than prior cadence. Do this during 2nd half of workout, with 5 min at ZR and normal cadence between each**
CoachComments: *target a minimum of 2000 feet of elevation gain during this ride

Title: Aerobic Run (Z1)
WorkoutDescription: Zone 1 Run. Make sure you descend the pace by getting faster throughout the workout. Start at the lower end of zone 1 and work your way toward the top by the end of the workout.

Title: TRX (custom routine)
WorkoutDescription: All exercises for 2 sets of 10 reps. Take 30 seconds between exercises. - Single Leg Squat - Sprinters Start - TRX Suspended Lunge - Hamstring Curl - Atomic Push-up - Side Plank (work up to 30 seconds each side) - Plank (work up to 30 seconds) - TRX Back Extentions - Single Arm Rotating Row - Swimmers Pull - Standing Y 2 sets of 12 reps of: -Monster Walk -Eccentric Calf Raises

Title: Tempo Ride #2 (Z2 2 X 30 min reps @ low cad)
WorkoutDescription: Warmup 25 min @ZR/Z1 Main Set 2 X 30 minutes at Z2 and a cadence of 70rpm with 5 min @ZR and 90rpm between each Cooldown To final ride time @ZR/Z1
CoachComments: *target a minimum of 2500 feet of elevation gain during this ride

Title: Recovery/Aerobic (ZR/Z1) Transition Run, as you feel
WorkoutDescription: Start your T run within 10 minutes after the bike ride. Start the run in ZR and descend pace (if you feel good) throughout the run into Z1. Finish toward the top of Z1.

Title: Lap Swimming
AthleteComments: *07/01/2018 Tara Strassburg: 😳 That’s a long swim 🤣*

Title: Master's Swim
WorkoutDescription: Swim with your master's group and summarize what you did in the notes

Title: Eccentric Calf Raises
WorkoutDescription: Do 3 sets of 12 reps on each leg. Each rep is carried out by standing on the ball of your foot (on a step), lowering slowly with one leg over a 2-3 second period (full range of motion), and then lifting back to the top with both feet quickly. These will help strengthen and stretch your calves.

Title: Aerobic Z1 Ride #5 (CAP Intervals) + Z2
WorkoutDescription: Warmup 10-30 minutes @ZR/Z1 Main Set Ride 3 x 15 minutes at the top of your Z1, but not over. Allow 5 minute ZR recovery between the intervals. Cool Down Ride any remaining time in Z1 but finish with the final 45 minutes at Z2!
CoachComments: *we need to start accumulating some serious elevation during your Sat/Sun rides. this may mean doing part of your long ride on the trainer, riding Mt Everest in Zwift. Let's aim for 6000 ft of elevation gain (at a minimum) this weekend between the two rides

Title: Bodywork - daily!
WorkoutDescription: Body work: 10 min foam rolling followed by 10 min of stretching Foam Roll 10 min - Light foam rolling, spending approximately 1-2 minutes on each of the following: -Calves -Soleus -IT bands -Hamstrings -Gluteals -Adductors -Lower back -Scapular muscles. Spend extra time on any particularly tight/painful areas. Be very careful not to roll on joints, or other areas with thin soft tissue cover. Stretching: Focus on targeting the flexibility of the glutes, hamstrings, quads, calves, and hipflexors. Ease into all stretching activities with muscles that are already warmed up. Hold all stretches for at least 30s.

Title: Aerobic/Tempo Ride #1 (Z1/Z2)
WorkoutDescription: Bike 190 minutes at Z1, then 50 minutes @ Z2. Descend the pace throughout the ride and finish toward the top of Z2. **Keep cadence at 85-90 rpm throughout unless using QT2 bike stimulation cadence chart (as given by coach).

Title: Aerobic Transition Run (Z1)
WorkoutDescription: Start your T run within 10 minutes after the bike ride. Run duration at zone and make sure you descend the pace by getting faster throughout the workout. Start at the lower end of zone 1 and work your way toward the top by the end of the workout.

Title: MTB-moderate effort
WorkoutDescription: Ride mostly in Z1/Z2 on a rolling course. Some Z3 is OK on hills. In/out of saddle on hills. Off-road, if possible.

Title: Recovery/Aerobic (ZR/Z1) Transition Run, as you feel

Title: Eccentric Calf Raises
WorkoutDescription: Do 3 sets of 12 reps on each leg. Each rep is carried out by standing on the ball of your foot (on a step), lowering slowly with one leg over a 2-3 second period (full range of motion), and then lifting back to the top with both feet quickly. These will help strengthen and stretch your calves.

Title: Tempo Fartlek (Z3) Run #2: Speed Ladders
WorkoutDescription: Warmup 10-15 minutes easy. Include 3 sets of the following ladder at Z3 effort for the ""fast"" intervals: 1 min fast/1 min easy easy 2 min fast/2 min easy easy 3 min fast/5 min easy easy *goal is same pace for all fast sections Run any remaining time in ZR/Z1

Title: Bodywork - daily!
WorkoutDescription: Body work: 10 min foam rolling followed by 10 min of stretching Foam Roll 10 min - Light foam rolling, spending approximately 1-2 minutes on each of the following: -Calves -Soleus -IT bands -Hamstrings -Gluteals -Adductors -Lower back -Scapular muscles. Spend extra time on any particularly tight/painful areas. Be very careful not to roll on joints, or other areas with thin soft tissue cover. Stretching: Focus on targeting the flexibility of the glutes, hamstrings, quads, calves, and hipflexors. Ease into all stretching activities with muscles that are already warmed up. Hold all stretches for at least 30s.

Title: Recovery ZR Ride #2 (single-leg pedaling)
WorkoutDescription: Warmup 10-20 minutes easy spinning Main Set Ride aerobic pace in ZR.Some riding in Zone 1 during drills is fine. Do the following 3 times: 10 seconds of high rpm, 10 seconds higher, 10 seconds max rpm and then recover for 60 seconds. Then do this 3 times: 30 seconds left followed by 30 seconds right-leg dominant pedaling (other leg soft-pedals). Repeat both of these drills a TOTAL of 4 times, all in the small chain ring. Cooldown To final ride time @ZR

Title: Recovery Transition Run (ZR)
WorkoutDescription: Start your T run within 10 minutes after the bike ride. Run duration @ ZR with a cadence of at least 88 steps per minute.

Title: Adaptation Phase Lift
WorkoutDescription: o There is no warm-up required for each exercise since the rep range is very high and therefore relatively light weights are used. o Rest time between sets needs only to be about 1.5 minutes. Overall, each workout should only take about 30-40 minutes. o Use light weights, and really focus on using proper form. There will be plenty of time to lift heavy weights during the max strength phase. This adaptation phase is just preparing your body for that. The focus is on stretching the soft tissue. Just going through the motions! Record your results in your Strength Log!

Title: Aerobic Z1 w/Run Drills
WorkoutDescription: Run Aerobic Z1. Include 4 x 50 meters of running drills with easy 50 meter jog in-between: 1) Heel Lifts 2) Grapevines--alternating one foot in front of the other 3) Fast Feet--focus on landing on the balls of your feet in very short and quick steps 4) Skips--drive tall and slow, alternate arms 5) Backwards running 6) High Knees Cool down to total run time @Z1

Title: Max Strength Phase Lift
WorkoutDescription: o A proper warm-up should consist of 12 reps at 50% of the weight for your first set followed by 3 reps at 75% of the weight for your first set. After this, you will be well prepared to do the full weight of your first set. o Rest time between sets for the max strength phase is about 3 minutes in order to allow a solid recovery and maximum strength before the next set. Record your results in your Strength Log!
